               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1714" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1714" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1714" type="surname" value="PATTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1714" type="given" value="HENRY DALTON"></interp>HENRY DALTON PATTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to John Goss Fleay, of Deptford, The prisoner came to his shop on the 20th of July, and I showed her a box of artificial flowers—I observed her conceal one under her cloak—she selected one, and some other things for which she paid—I put them in paper, and she left—I called her back, and asked if she had not something that did not be<lb></lb>long to her—she said, "No"—I brought her into the shop, and asked her again—she denied it, but on lifting up her cloak this one was produced—it is not the one I had sold her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> She had bought a flower? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yet, and some other things which came to 5 3/4 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—she then gave me 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and I gave her 6 1/4 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in change—I did not charge her with this, and take the 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for it—we had had information before—I did not say "I must take 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. more, be<lb></lb>cause you have another flower."</p>
               <p>
